 18  /-- A filter `f` is Cauchy if for every entourage `r`, there exists an
 19    `s ∈ f` such that `s × s ⊆ r`. This is a generalization of Cauchy
 20    sequences, because if `a : ℕ → α` then the filter of sets containing
 21    cofinitely many of the `a n` is Cauchy iff `a` is a Cauchy sequence. -/
 22  def cauchy (f : filter α) := f ≠ ⊥ ∧ filter.prod f f ≤ (𝓤 α)

 24  /-- A set `s` is called *complete*, if any Cauchy filter `f` such that `s ∈ f`
 25  has a limit in `s` (formally, it satisfies `f ≤ 𝓝 x` for some `x ∈ s`). -/
 26  def is_complete (s : set α) := ∀f, cauchy f → f ≤ principal s → ∃x∈s, f ≤ 𝓝 x

346  /-! ### Sequentially complete space
347  
348  In this section we prove that a uniform space is complete provided that it is sequentially complete
349  (i.e., any Cauchy sequence converges) and its uniformity filter admits a countable generating set.
350  In particular, this applies to (e)metric spaces, see the files `topology/metric_space/emetric_space` and
351  `topology/metric_space/basic`.
352  
353  More precisely, we assume that there is a sequence of entourages `U_n` such that any other
354  entourage includes one of `U_n`. Then any Cauchy filter `f` generates a decreasing sequence of
355  sets `s_n ∈ f` such that `s_n × s_n ⊆ U_n`. Choose a sequence `x_n∈s_n`. It is easy to show
356  that this is a Cauchy sequence. If this sequence converges to some `a`, then `f ≤ 𝓝 a`. -/
357  
358  namespace sequentially_complete
359  
360  variables {f : filter α} (hf : cauchy f) {U : ℕ → set (α × α)}

src                 └────┘          └────┘         ┴   └─┘    ┴
typ                 └────┘          └────┘         ┴   └─┘    ┴
doc                                 └────┘
361    (U_mem : ∀ n, U n ∈ 𝓤 α) (U_le : ∀ s ∈ 𝓤 α, ∃ n, U n ⊆ s)

src                      ┴ ┴                  ┴    ┴  ┴     ┴
